@Node INEA3 "Invasion -- Earth > Only The Dead [#3]"

 @{b}Only The Dead [#3]@{ub} (1998)
 
 Radcliffe and his men set off in pursuit of Friday, who has hi-jacked a car.
 
 Given the security breach attempted by the other abductees. Reece orders that
 Tucker be confined. She is to see neurosurgeon Group Captain Preston.
 
 The remaining abductee dies on the operating table as Preston attempts to
 remove the implant.
 
 Terrell is still clamming up in response to interrogation. Throughout the
 episode we see his story emerge in flashback. Back in 1944 the crashed ship
 (seen at the start of chapter one) contained two survivors, one of whom was
 shot. The remaining being was taken to a remote sanatorium, where Terrell was
 given leave to try and communicate with it. It appeared to be a peaceful
 creature, but Terrell was forced back to his bomb disposal duties before he
 could establish communication with it.
 
 By drawing a pictograph of the alien distress symbol in a field, Terrell
 allowed himself to be abducted by the creature's own people, known as the
 'Echoes'. Since 1944, travelling close to light speed as one of their pilots,
 he has aged very little relative to humans on Earth.
 
 Progress on unravelling the technology of Terrell's crashed pod is slow and
 the team need his help. When a flash in the sky is followed by radar picking
 up an unidentified craft, Tucker manages to persuade Terrell to help them. He
 identifies the incoming craft as Echo, and not hostile, but a strike is
 already underway and the Echo is shot down. Drake manages to save the injured
 pilot when its craft plunges into a lake. After frantic attempts to
 resuscitate the Echo pilot, it regains consciousness long enough to speak to
 Terrell. Just as its condition stabilises Terrell kills it. Distressed, he
 explains that the Echo asked to die. The flash in the sky was the mothership.
 The Echoes detonated their own ships engines, committing mass suicide rather
 than let themselves be changed and put to a violent purpose by the nDs.
 
 Terrell reveals what he knows of the nDs' plan - before he wouldn't speak for
 fear of endangering the Echoes. He explains that the Echoes have been watching
 Earth. The nDs have been spreading throughout the universe, devising means of
 using every life-form on planets that they colonise. Earth and the life-forms
 on it are similar to the Echoes' home world - the fate that awaits Earth would
 have befallen the Echoes next.
 
 The Echoes are pacifists, and even if they had been disposed towards war,
 their planet is too far away for support to reach us in time. When Terrell was
 shot down the nDs knew that he might pass the truth on to mankind, so now they
 have stepped up their campaign. They can't be stopped. Drake is distressed by
 the realisation that he has precipitated the whole thing.
 
 Friday reaches the town of Kirkhaven and he is undergoing alarming physical
 changes. The wound on Tucker's arm begins to heal as nD tissue.
 
