@Node INEA5 "Invasion -- Earth > The Battle More Costly [#5]"

 @{b}The Battle More Costly [#5]@{ub} (1998)
 
 Preston works feverishly on developing a toxin. Finally, she succeeds in a
 test tube test. In Kirkhaven, Dr. Vickers has been working flat out treating
 the townspeople. Shortly after he leaves the very ill Jenny Marchant, she is
 abducted by the nDs.
 
 An elated Preston reports her findings to Reece. They need a living subject to
 test it on. Tucker volunteers herself, despite Drakes protests.
 
 DS Holland makes the connection between Friday and the body in the reservoir.
 She calls Radcliffe to identify him. Preston and Stewart begin to examine him,
 realising that he must have been carrying something in his blood.
 
 Jenny Marchant is returned by the nDs, confused, but otherwise seeming
 healthy. An examination reveals that someone has accessed her veins. Both
 Vickers and Holland draw a blank. Tucker and Drake head for Kirkhaven. Preston
 is receiving regular samples from Tucker on which she is conducting trials of
 potential nD toxins. Working together, they deduce what is happening: the
 disease was carried by Friday and spread via the water. It causes the
 increased production of serotonin in the infected person, which causes the
 side effects that manifest themselves in symptoms of the illness. Marchant was
 'cured' because the nDs drained off the serotonin. The terrible truth dawns on
 Tucker - the nDs are farming us. They need our brain chemicals to run their
 advanced biotechnology. She is to be part of this plan as well - a shepherd to
 mind the giant farm.
 
 Alone, Drake and Tucker digest what they have learned. She rejects him again,
 terrified of what she may be turning into. As he wanders pensively through
 Kirkhaven he meets Holland, who invites him home with her. In their
 conversation, it emerges that there is a shortage of men in Kirkhaven. This
 registers with Drake and he calls Radcliffe to check out the statistics.
 Holland tries to seduce him, but all he can think about is Tucker and he runs
 back to her. She is moved to see him and they make love.
 
 Radcliffe finds that the population statistics are relevant. The nDs have been
 manipulating the gender of selected communities, of which Kirkhaven is only
 one, feminising them in an attempt to produce humans who could be made to
 reproduce asexually.
 
 Nick manages to invent a detector that gives advance warning of an nD portal
 about to open. Delighted with this edge, Knox pushes Reece to give the order
 to move in on Kirkhaven. Reece is reluctant and his team realise that they
 haven't got the reinforcements they need. In Kirkhaven, Tucker and Drake
 realise that the toxin is working. Her stigma is finally starting to heal as
 normal human flesh. The toxin is manufactured and loaded into ammunition. With
 the twin advantages of the toxin and the detector, the unit moves in on
 Kirkhaven, repelling the nDs as they come for the townspeople. After the
 attack, there is silence, and the toxin appears to be working.
 
 Preston proposes a sure fire means of getting the toxin to the whole of the nD
 civilisation: delivering it to them via the infected townspeople. Reluctantly,
 Reece gives the order for her to proceed. Reece calls Bentley in again to
 witness the nDs coming back for the townspeople. He is convinced and orders
 reinforcements to be sent.
 
 After a still night, they dare to believe that the toxin is working. As they
 wait, Nick's detector blips. The signal goes off the scale. Dismayed, they
 look out to see that a vast, threatening structure - a lacuna, has appeared
 above the town. The nDs have stepped up their campaign again.
 
