@Node INEA6 "Invasion -- Earth > The Shatterer Of Worlds [#6]"

 @{b}The Shatterer Of Worlds [#6]@{ub} (1998)
 
 On seeing the nD structure, Tucker realises that Preston's toxin has not
 worked and that the process she is undergoing will continue. Bentley now has
 the proof he needs and artillery is in place to attack the phenomenon. Reece
 argues that they need time to investigate the lacuna, that force will not
 work, but Bentley feels he has no option and orders a futile strike to go
 ahead, causing Reece to pull Tucker, Drake and the team out of the area before
 they can gather all the data they are after. When it becomes apparent that the
 strike has not worked, Bentley hands control back to Reece, acknowledging that
 his people are the experts and our only line of defence.
 
 When Tucker and Drake are ordered back to Field HQ, Nick makes a case for
 staying near the phenomenon. He has picked up some unfamiliar readings and
 needs to investigate them further. When he realises that it must be nD
 communication, he is excited by the chance this offers and without clearance,
 heads back to gather more data. He makes a fatal attempt to communicate.
 
 Tucker volunteers herself to Preston for tests - understanding the process she
 is undergoing may be the key to beating the nDs. Preston is as professional as
 ever, although she is, by now, straining to keep her faith in science's
 ability to provide answers. Drake is distraught by the knowledge that the
 changes in Tucker are irreversible.
 
 Working from the limited data they gathered in the vicinity of the lacuna,
 Tucker and Drake realise that objects entering it leave a channel behind them
 from which information can be received. In the absence of a more sophisticated
 probe, they resolve to attach instrumentation to a plane and fly it in. Reece
 must decide between Drake and Knox to act as pilot. The job falls to Knox, who
 sends back useful data before being lost in action.
 
 Preston has been analysing the progress of nD cell's in Tucker's body and
 realises that non-living matter is an obstacle to them. This, together with
 results from samples taken around the lacuna, leads her reluctantly towards
 the idea that denying the nDs access to living matter is the only thing that
 will stop them. Taking into account the energy of the structure, Tucker works
 out how much ground will need to be scorched - only a nuclear device is
 powerful enough. As she works, Tucker realises that she will have to be
 eliminated as well.
 
 Naturally there is some urgency to finding an alternative to this drastic
 action. Tucker finds that the structure of the nD matrix extends to higher
 dimensions. More of them could be about to appear at prepared sites throughout
 the planet. Her calculations show that a small release of energy at a critical
 point inside the lacuna will destabilise the whole structure. Tucker and Drake
 make practice runs on a simulator rigged up using the telemetry from Knox's
 flight. Her insights are precise and far reaching - she is starting to think
 like an nD. Desperate to assert her humanity, she makes love to Drake.
 
 Eventually Drake and Tucker make the run and when the phenomenon starts to
 disintegrate, it seems that their mission has been a success. But as soon as
 they escape, another one appears, folded down from a higher dimension. They
 realise that nD resources are practically infinite. Scorched earth, is the
 only option. We have to show the nDs that we would rather wipe out our own
 species than give ourselves over to them. Tucker realises that she must
 sacrifice herself to be free. As the order to deploy a nuclear weapon comes
 through, Tucker goes to Kirkhaven. She smiles as she is enveloped by the
 blast. It is the only way, but she has beaten them.
 
